Sure, you can use the following code in your Discord bot's message event listener function to automatically reply with "hi" when someone mentions your bot:

```javascript
const Discord = require('discord.js');
const client = new Discord.Client();

// Replace "your_bot_token" with your actual bot token
client.login('your_bot_token');

client.on('message', message => {
  // Ignore messages sent by the bot itself
  if (message.author.bot) return;

  // Check if the message contains a mention of your bot's ID
  if (message.mentions.has(client.user.id)) {
    // Reply with "hi"
    message.channel.send('hi');
  }
});
```

This script uses the `discord.js` library to create a simple bot and replies with "hi" whenever it's mentioned. Make sure to replace `your_bot_token` with your actual bot token when running the script.

I apologize for the confusion! Here's a code that you can run in your Google Chrome console to send an automatic "hi" when someone pings you.

Important Note: Automating user accounts in Discord (also known as "self-bots") is against Discord's Terms of Service, and your account can be banned for using such scripts. Use it at your own risk.

1. Press `Ctrl + Shift + J` on your keyboard to open the Console tab in Chrome Developer Tools.

2. Paste the following code into the console, and press Enter to run it:

```javascript
const authToken = 'your_auth_token'; // Replace with your personal Discord auth token

const ws = new WebSocket('wss://gateway.discord.gg/?v=6&encoding=json');
const sendMessage = (channelID, messageContent) => {
    fetch(`https://discord.com/api/v8/channels/${channelID}/messages`, {
        method: 'POST',
        body: JSON.stringify({content: messageContent}),
        headers: {
            'Authorization': `Bot ${authToken}`,
            'Content-Type': 'application/json'
        }
    });
};

ws.onmessage = (event) => {
    const packet = JSON.parse(event.data);

    if (packet.op === 10) {
        const heartbeatInterval = packet.d.heartbeat_interval;
        setInterval(() => {
            ws.send(JSON.stringify({op: 1, d: null}));
        }, heartbeatInterval);

        ws.send(JSON.stringify({
            op: 2,
            d: {
                token: authToken,
                properties: {$browser: 'b1'},
                compress: false,
                large_threshold: 50,
                presence: {status: 'online'}
            }
        }));
    }

    if (packet.t === 'MESSAGE_CREATE') {
        const message = packet.d;
        if (message.mentions && message.mentions.some(mention => mention.id === userID)) {
            sendMessage(message.channel_id, 'hi');
        }
    }
};
```

3. Replace `'your_auth_token'` with your actual personal Discord auth token.

You can find your personal token using the following steps:

1. Press `Ctrl + Shift + I` in your Discord window to open the Developer Tools.
2. Click the `Applications` tab, then `Local Storage` > `https://discord.com`.
3. Look for the entry with the key '`token`'. The value in double quotes is your personal auth token.

Again, modifying and automating your personal Discord account may result in a ban or suspension of your account. Use this code at your own risk.

