1. Make sure you have wrapped your form component with the `FormProvider` component from `react-hook-form` library. This component provides the necessary context for the form to work properly.

2. Check if the control component that renders your input field is using the `control` prop correctly. This prop should be set to the `control` object returned by `useForm` hook.

3. Check if you are rendering the `ErrorMessage` component from `react-hook-form` library below your input component. This component will show validation errors if any.

Here is an updated code snippet that implements the above suggestions:

```jsx
import React from 'react';
import { useForm, FormProvider, Controller } from 'react-hook-form';

const MyForm = () => {
  const methods = useForm();

  const onSubmit = (data) => {
    console.log(data);
  };

  return (
    <FormProvider {...methods}>
      <form onSubmit={methods.handleSubmit(onSubmit)}>
        <Controller
          name="firstName"
          control={methods.control}
          rules={{ required: true }}
          render={({ field }) => (
            <>
              <label>First Name</label>
              <input type="text" {...field} />
              {methods.errors.firstName && (
                <span>This field is required</span>
              )}
            </>
          )}
        />

        <Controller
          name="lastName"
          control={methods.control}
          rules={{ required: true }}
          render={({ field }) => (
            <>
              <label>Last Name</label>
              <input type="text" {...field} />
              {methods.errors.lastName && (
                <span>This field is required</span>
              )}
            </>
          )}
        />

        <button type="submit">Submit</button>
      </form>
    </FormProvider>
  );
};

export default MyForm;
```

In this example, I have used two `Controller` components to render two input fields, one for first name and one for last name. The `rules` prop is set to `{ required: true }` to ensure that both fields are required. The `ErrorMessage` component is rendered below the input field to show validation errors if any.

